<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-605-114  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 605 114.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Journal of Systems and Software  May 1990 v12 n2 p125(13).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A framework for the support of a common structural level forsoftware-, data base-, and knowledge-based systems. (Special issueon the role of language in programming.) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Motschnig-Pitrik, R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Currently, many languages, tools, and techniques are used for thedevelopment of software systems, including data base- andknowledge-based systems.andP;  Although underlying languages employstructuring concepts such as classification, modularization,generalization, perspectives, etc., these common concepts remainovershadowed by differing terminology and notations among diverseapproaches in software engineering, data bases, and knowledgerepresentation.andP;  As a consequence, we have to cope with a largenumber of specific but incomplete tools to support the developmentof software systems.andP;  This situation appears inconvenient, sincethe still more complex and ambitious requirements on softwaresystems call for integrated solutions concerning softwareengineering environments.andP;  As a starting point toward integration,in this article we concentrate on structuring concepts and theirsupport.andP;  While the central role of structuring in softwaredevelopment, as well as maintenance, is well established, auniform support of some set of structuring concepts has not yetbeen achieved.andP;  Therefore, we present a catalog of generallyuseful structuring concepts, explain their derivation, and suggesta self-contained language called SFW (Structuring Framework) and atool (SFW-TOOL) to provide means for a general and uniformspecification and support of the structure of software systems.andO;(Reprinted by permission of the publisher.)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ProgrammingData Base LanguagesKnowledge-Based SystemsSoftware Engineering.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Generalization. (chart)Building blocks in SFW. (chart)Parts of a SFW SUn interface. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>